\subsubsection{Data Analysis}
Sessions were audio-recorded with unanimous participant consent. Two CTSI staff present at the session produced a master transcript and summary documents according to standard CE Studio procedures. Two researchers then independently performed inductive thematic analysis on the master transcript without a predetermined coding frame. Codes were grouped iteratively into themes; disagreements were resolved through discussion to consensus. Themes were retained when supported by multiple participants and corroborated by observational findings or quantitative response items where applicable. The master transcript and CTSI summaries are released as supplementary materials.
\subsection{Supplementary Expert Consultation}
To examine whether the patterns identified in the CE Studio extended beyond the lay participant cohort, we conducted a supplementary one-hour consultation with an independent public health professional (hereafter ``the consultant'') with both professional experience serving older and underserved populations and personal experience as a former caregiver. The consultation took place three days after the CE Studio. The consultant was familiar with the application's intended use through a prior briefing but was not provided the CE Studio findings before or during the consultation. Her observations were recorded and summarized by CTSI staff. They are reported in §3.5 as a corroborating expert view from a different professional vantage rather than as an independent confirmatory study. The summary is released as a supplementary material.
\section{Results}
\subsection{Physical Capture Incapacity Observed During Attempted Use}
During attempted use, participants encountered two physical limitations consistently. Mouth opening was inadequate for the intraoral exposure required: participants could not extend their lips and cheeks far enough to expose the dental arches the model is trained to read. Hand stability during the capture motion was insufficient for the framing precision the on-device blur detector requires for acceptance.

These observations surfaced organically during demonstration. The retractor question, ordinarily encountered only by researchers familiar with intraoral photography, was raised by a participant unprompted:
\begin{quoting}
Do you have a device that comes with it to take your lips out of the way?
\end{quoting}
The research team's real-time response was twofold. A retractor accessory was acknowledged as available for purchase. A participant immediately objected:
\begin{quoting}
Is that really necessary? Having to buy something in addition to make it work is not helpful.
\end{quoting}
The team's second suggestion in the same exchange was:
\begin{quoting}
You can hold your lips only like this and someone else can take the photo for you.
\end{quoting}
This was offered as a workaround, not a design proposition. It became the operative frame for the cohort.
Another participant, after attempting the app, described the capture problem in operational terms:
\begin{quoting}
We tried the app, and I am still not sure how to take the picture. You need the phone to make a sound that the picture was actually taken. How do you know the app is working right? It is hard to use.
\end{quoting}
Two further participants returned to the photograph as the load-bearing failure point:
\begin{quoting}
I think it would be very difficult to take a good picture. And I think if you don't have a good picture the whole thing fails. Everything hinges on a good picture. And I think taking a good quality picture would be very difficult for a senior to do.
\end{quoting}
\begin{quoting}
Even with the little camera gadget you can buy and put on your phone, even that gadget camera would be hard to use for a senior.
\end{quoting}
Contemporary smartphone cameras are sensor-adequate for caries imaging~\parencite{kargozar2024teledentistry}. The barrier observed here was not optics. It was the embodied task of self-photography in a region of one's own body one cannot directly see, performed by hands that may have lost dexterity, with a mouth that may not open wide enough to expose what the model is trained to read. The research team, having designed and built the application, did not anticipate this barrier in their own cohort; the lay user attempting unassisted use at home is less likely to anticipate or compensate for it.
\subsection{The Convergence on Caregiver-as-Operator}
In the discussion following attempted use, a participant who had cared for her elderly mother offered a complete reframing of the deployment unit:
\begin{quoting}
I was thinking about how it was when I was taking care of my elderly mom years ago. And I remember what it was like to get her ready to leave the house for appointments and what an ordeal it was to prepare for appointments. And I wonder how her life would have been different by using this app instead.
\end{quoting}
\begin{quoting}
I see this app more of a caregiver responsibility and not on the elderly person so much. Caregivers would need the app on their phone and know how to use it on the elderly person. My mom did not even have a cell phone. There is no way she would have access to this. It would be on me as her caregiver to use the app for her. To have one appointment instead of two would be huge. The app would cut down on appointments but would be for me as the caregiver to use, not my mom. You may see that this applies to other seniors who are elderly with physical conditions that limit mobility or other functions.
\end{quoting}
The facilitator, herself a former caregiver, endorsed the framing immediately:
\begin{quoting}
I was the caretaker of my parents and my dad was big and tall and I was rolling that wheelchair to appointments and the chair would scratch up base boards and by the time we got there I was exhausted. So, hold that thought about caregivers. I wish I would have had that app.
\end{quoting}
After the break, the facilitator returned to the caregiver frame as the organizing question for the remaining discussion:
\begin{quoting}
We were talking about caregivers. What is the value of this tool for caregivers? It was an ordeal to go to in-person appointments. We did a lot of wear and tear on baseboards and doorways but also on our bodies. We didn't have telehealth. This would have been a great resource for me.
\end{quoting}
A second caregiver participant joined:
\begin{quoting}
It would help me and my mom too. My mom had cancer, and she was limited too. So, anything that would help get past the limitations would have been great.
\end{quoting}
The trajectory is recoverable from the transcript as a sequence. Capture failure was observed during attempted use. A retractor accessory was proposed by the team and rejected by a participant. A proxy-operator workaround was proposed by the team in the same exchange. A caregiver participant elevated the workaround to a full reframing of the appropriate operator. The facilitator endorsed it from her own caregiving experience. A second caregiver participant confirmed it. The framing was not directed by the research team; the team's role in the relevant turns was limited to answering questions and demonstrating the application. The released master transcript permits independent verification of this sequence.
\subsection{Supporting Evidence for Caregiver-Mediated Deployment}
Three additional threads bear on the deployment question, each independently weakening the patient-as-operator default.
\subsubsection{Trust mediation}
Concerns about AI diagnosis surfaced as distinct from concerns about app reliability, hardware, or privacy:
\begin{quoting}
AI is doing the diagnosis. That is scary to me.
\end{quoting}
Another participant identified the structural prerequisite for trust:
\begin{quoting}
What if I take a scan and call my doctor and they do not know what I am talking about? Dentists have to be on board with this for it to work.
\end{quoting}
A mean Average Precision of 0.748 has no clinical referent for these participants. What they are measuring is whether the result will be honored by the provider and whether the provider's workflow can act on it. A caregiver---typically younger, more familiar with the application, and capable of describing the result in clinically interpretable terms---mediates this calibration in ways the older adult navigating the conversation alone does not.
\subsubsection{Appointment burden}
Participants who had been caregivers described the embodied cost of in-person appointments in concrete terms. The facilitator's wheelchair-and-baseboard account, quoted above, is the most vivid; the same theme recurred for the participant whose mother had cancer. The asymmetry is consequential: the appointment burden in the geriatric population falls disproportionately on the caregiver, and a screening tool that reduces appointment frequency is principally a tool that reduces caregiver burden.
\subsubsection{Scam vulnerability}
Multiple participants and the facilitator returned to the scam exposure of unsupported older adults. The facilitator offered the case of her own father: \textit{``My dad never answered his phone but would look at the mail.''} A participant working in healthcare extended the point to her client population:
\begin{quoting}
It's difficult for my clients who live with substance disorders and other things to trust sharing information. A lot of times they've been scammed for other apps for various reasons. They are very reluctant to share their medical and insurance information. Perhaps if the providers initiate the conversation, they would be more open.
\end{quoting}
An older adult asked to download and trust a health application unsupported is operating in the same threat environment as the scam attempts she has been trained to refuse. Caregiver-mediated deployment routes around this; provider-initiated deployment routes around it further.
\subsubsection{Pandemic context}
The pandemic was raised by a participant unprompted:
\begin{quoting}
And I think back to COVID, and this would have been very helpful during those times.
\end{quoting}
Geriatric care disruption during the pandemic disproportionately affected the population that depends on caregiver-mediated access to providers~\parencite{doi:10.1177/10775587211062405}; a tool that reduces in-person appointment requirements has highest marginal value precisely when such appointments are hardest to obtain.
\subsection{Quantitative Patterns}
Interest in OralScan was unanimous. Every participant said they would use the tool, and every participant said they would discuss it with their dentist. Willingness to pay was reported by 6 of 13 (46.2\%) (Table~\ref{tab:usability}). Approximately half the cohort indicated the tool was easy to use; approximately half did not---a split that would be ordinary for a low-stakes consumer application and is consequential for one designed to detect disease in a population at high baseline risk.
\begin{table}[!htbp]
\centering
\caption{Quantitative usability responses.}
\label{tab:usability}
\begin{tabular}{lr}
\toprule
\textbf{Response} & \textbf{Proportion} \\
\midrule
Expressed interest in using the app & 100\% (13/13) \\
Would discuss app with their dentist & 100\% (13/13) \\
\addlinespace
Willing to pay for the app & 46.2\% (6/13) \\
\addlinespace
Indicated the app was easy to use & 53.8\% (7/13) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
These responses describe the same pattern observed during attempted use. Judgment of whether the tool should exist is rapid, social, and abstract. Judgment of whether one can use it is slow, embodied, and contingent on capacities that participants---and the research team---encountered only at the moment of attempted use. An evaluation pipeline that asks the first question and infers the second produces favorable adoption forecasts that the embodied user does not meet.

\subsection{Corroborating Findings from the Expert Consultation}
The supplementary consultation produced observations that align with, and in places extend, the CE Studio findings. They are reported here as a corroborating expert view rather than as independent confirmation.

On the appropriate operator, the consultant proposed that the application could be operated by a family caregiver, with trained healthcare workers as an alternative configuration for older adults with mobility limitations or without family caregivers available. Her primary recommendation aligned with the cohort's organic conclusion: the operator should not be assumed to be the patient.

On capture instrumentation, the consultant proposed an endoscope camera with integrated light as the appropriate capture instrument for patients with limited hand stability. She estimated retail cost at \$30 to \$40, noted that versions with integrated screens are available at the upper end of that range, and proposed bulk procurement subsidized through public health campaigns as a deployment mechanism. The device, in her framing, addresses both the mouth-exposure and the hand-stability limitations observed in §3.1. A screen-equipped variant carries an additional implication: it would eliminate dependence on the patient's smartphone entirely, allowing the trained operator to capture, view, and store screening images on a dedicated device without requiring the patient to own a compatible phone, manage app installation, or maintain a cellular data plan.

On infrastructure constraints, the consultant identified two friction points that further favor operator-mediated deployment. First, contemporary smartphone form factors are awkward to maneuver close to the mouth of an older adult with limited neck mobility. Second, many low-income older adults use government-issued flip phones rather than smartphones, eliminating the patient-facing pathway for that subset. She further noted that smartphone ownership turns over every one to two years, and data migration between devices remains imperfect even on modern platforms.

On AI-mediated diagnosis, the consultant recommended that screening results be communicated to patients through a healthcare professional rather than directly from the application, consistent with the trust-mediation finding in §3.3. She indicated, separately, an independently held skepticism of AI applications in healthcare based on direct experience with AI-mediated customer service and medical-record summarization. Her recommendation that results be routed through a healthcare professional was offered against this background of skepticism, not despite it.

On deployment context, the consultant identified skilled nursing facilities and incarcerated populations as additional contexts in which the operator-trained-staff model would be applicable, alongside community-dwelling older adults with family caregivers.

The consultant had not been briefed on the CE Studio findings prior to the consultation. Her recommendations therefore offer a corroborating expert view from a different professional vantage rather than independent confirmation. The summary is released as a supplementary material.

\section{Discussion}
\subsection{Principal Finding}
The physical incapacity observed in §3.1 is not closed by improving the model. It is not closed by improving the hardware. It is closed by changing who holds the phone.

AI-powered geriatric health screening tools should be designed primarily as caregiver instruments. The caregiver---a family member, a community health worker, a nursing-home staff member, a clinical care worker---has the dexterity to perform the capture, the cognitive flexibility to interpret the result in conversation with the provider, and operational familiarity with the patient's body that the patient may not have for parts of her own mouth. The appropriate deployment unit is the caregiver--patient dyad, not the patient alone.

The asymmetry between expressed interest and embodied capacity reported in §3.4, and the corroborating expert recommendations in §3.5, point in the same direction (Table~\ref{tab:pivot-logic}).
