\begin{abstract}
\noindent\textbf{Background:} Among U.S. adults aged 65+, 79\% own a smartphone, and the geriatric dental disease burden is projected to nearly double by 2050. Mobile health (mHealth) tools for older adults are designed around the assumption that the patient is the operator. Whether that assumption fits the embodied reality of the geriatric population, and whether current evaluation infrastructure can detect when it does not, are unsettled.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Objective:} To examine the patient-as-operator assumption and its evaluation pipeline through formative human-factors investigation of an AI-powered oral health screening application.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Methods:} A Community Engagement (CE) Studio ($N=13$, ages 60--76) evaluated OralScan, an AI-powered smartphone application for intraoral disease screening built with the University at Buffalo School of Dental Medicine. Participants attempted to use the application during the session. A neutral community facilitator led a 70-minute discussion; Clinical and Translational Science Institute (CTSI) staff produced a master transcript and summary; two researchers independently performed inductive thematic analysis. Cohort size follows the formative human-factors precedent of \textcite{nielsen1993usability}. A supplementary one-hour consultation with an independent public health professional was conducted three days later as a corroborating expert view. The master transcript, CTSI summaries, expert consultation summary, and facilitator's discussion guide are released as supplementary materials.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Results:} Interest in the tool was unanimous (13/13); approximately half the cohort indicated the tool was easy to use and approximately half did not. During attempted use, participants could not open their mouths sufficiently for intraoral exposure, and hand stability was insufficient for steady capture. Discussion converged---in participants' own framing and the facilitator's endorsement, both drawing on personal caregiving experience---on the caregiver as the primary operator. Supporting evidence emerged on AI trust mediation, appointment burden, and scam vulnerability among unsupported older adults. The expert consultation produced corroborating recommendations on capture instrumentation, infrastructure constraints, and provider-mediated communication of results.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Conclusions:} AI-powered geriatric health screening tools should be designed primarily as caregiver instruments, with the patient-facing pathway as residual for the subset of older adults who can execute the capture themselves. The evaluation infrastructure that produced today's patient-first tools measures interest at the moment of demonstration rather than embodied execution under home conditions; tools shipped under this infrastructure reach the population through an interface a substantial subset cannot operate. The deployment pathway implied is workforce reorganization aligned with an operator paradigm already present at scale in institutional dental screening and informal home caregiving.
\vspace{0.8cm}

\noindent\textit{\textbf{Keywords:} mHealth; geriatric usability; AI in healthcare; human factors; caregiver-mediated care; community engagement; teledentistry; informal caregiving}
\end{abstract}
\clearpage
\section{Introduction}
Seventy-nine percent of U.S. adults aged 65 or older own a smartphone~\parencite{pew_mobile_fact_sheet}; among those aged 50+, the figure reached 91\% by early 2025~\parencite{aarp2025tech}. In the present study, every participant aged 60--76 expressed interest in an AI-powered oral screening application. Approximately half indicated the tool was easy to use.

These numbers describe a population not low on technology but heterogeneously distributed on the capacity to execute specific embodied tasks within it. Geriatric mHealth has progressed past the era when device ownership was the binding constraint; the remaining barrier is more particular, and is not yet addressed by the prevailing design vocabulary.

The clinical stakes are acute. Oral diseases account for 284.6 Disability-Adjusted Life-Years per 100{,}000~\parencite{PATEL2021e521}, and approximately 66\% of U.S. adults aged 65+ have periodontitis~\parencite{geriatrics6030076}, with bidirectional links to diabetes and cardiovascular disease and elevated risk of Alzheimer's (+69\%) and Parkinson's (+43\%)~\parencite{geriatrics6030076}. Caries burden among older adults is projected to nearly double by 2050~\parencite{frontiers2023oral}. Traditional Medicare covers almost no dental care~\parencite{apha2021medicare, commonwealth2025medicare}, and roughly one in five older adults forgoes dental visits because of cost~\parencite{Gunja2024Health}.

The case for scalable, low-friction, AI-assisted screening at home is strong. The prevailing design assumption for such tools is that the patient is the operator: the patient holds the phone, captures the data, receives the result, and, where appropriate, brings it to a provider. This was a reasonable inheritance from the user populations for which mobile health was first designed---younger users for whom self-management on a personal device was the appropriate frame. Current mobile app UIs present significant barriers to older adults because they are not systematically tailored to their physical, sensory, and cognitive needs~\parencite{bailey2025designing}. The assumption has been carried forward into geriatric mHealth largely unexamined.

We report a formative CE Studio investigation of OralScan, an AI-powered mobile screening application built with the University at Buffalo School of Dental Medicine. Participants attempted to use the application themselves; an unaffiliated facilitator led a structured discussion afterward; an independent public health professional was consulted three days later as a corroborating expert view. The findings bear on two related questions: whether the patient-as-operator assumption is the right design center for AI-powered geriatric oral health screening, and whether the evaluation infrastructure that produced today's patient-first tools is measuring the variable that determines deployment success.
\section{Materials and Methods}
\subsection{The OralScan System}
OralScan captures intraoral images on a consumer smartphone and returns segmentation overlays for six oral conditions: calculus/plaque, caries, oral lesions, gingivitis, hypodontia, and discoloration. Conditions were selected with collaborators at the University at Buffalo School of Dental Medicine on the basis of clinical prevalence and diagnostic significance in geriatric populations.

Image acceptability is screened on the device using a Laplacian-variance blur detector~\parencite{blur} and a quantized YOLOv11-Nano tooth-numbering model running in TensorFlow.js, providing sub-second capture feedback. Accepted images---typically three per screening session---are submitted to a fine-tuned YOLOv11-XL detection model~\parencite{yolo11_ultralytics} integrated with Meta's Segment Anything Model 2.1~\parencite{ravi2024sam2segmentimages}; bounding-box detections are converted into translucent overlays returned to the device. Local blur screening keeps data transfer well within standard cellular plan capacities. The deployed model achieves a mean Average Precision (mAP@0.50) of 0.748 averaged across the six conditions. Dataset composition, training configuration, and per-class detection performance appear in Appendix~A.
