\subsubsection{Session Structure}
The two-hour session opened with a 15-minute presentation introducing OralScan and a 10-minute interactive demonstration (Figure~\ref{fig:presentation}). Participants then attempted to use the application themselves, with research staff available to assist. This attempted-use phase produced the observational findings in §3.1; without it, the physical capture incapacity the discussion subsequently addressed would have been visible only through participant report. After a short break, a community facilitator unaffiliated with the research team led a 70-minute discussion (Figure~\ref{fig:facilitator}). Older adults in clinical research contexts can mirror the enthusiasm of researchers present in the room; an unaffiliated facilitator removes that pressure and permits skepticism to surface. The facilitator's discussion guide is released as supplementary material.
