These responses describe the same pattern observed during attempted use. Judgment of whether the tool should exist is rapid, social, and abstract. Judgment of whether one can use it is slow, embodied, and contingent on capacities that participants---and the research team---encountered only at the moment of attempted use. An evaluation pipeline that asks the first question and infers the second produces favorable adoption forecasts that the embodied user does not meet.

\subsection{Corroborating Findings from the Expert Consultation}
The supplementary consultation produced observations that align with, and in places extend, the CE Studio findings. They are reported here as a corroborating expert view rather than as independent confirmation.

On the appropriate operator, the consultant proposed that the application could be operated by a family caregiver, with trained healthcare workers as an alternative configuration for older adults with mobility limitations or without family caregivers available. Her primary recommendation aligned with the cohort's organic conclusion: the operator should not be assumed to be the patient.

On capture instrumentation, the consultant proposed an endoscope camera with integrated light as the appropriate capture instrument for patients with limited hand stability. She estimated retail cost at \$30 to \$40, noted that versions with integrated screens are available at the upper end of that range, and proposed bulk procurement subsidized through public health campaigns as a deployment mechanism. The device, in her framing, addresses both the mouth-exposure and the hand-stability limitations observed in §3.1. A screen-equipped variant carries an additional implication: it would eliminate dependence on the patient's smartphone entirely, allowing the trained operator to capture, view, and store screening images on a dedicated device without requiring the patient to own a compatible phone, manage app installation, or maintain a cellular data plan.

On infrastructure constraints, the consultant identified two friction points that further favor operator-mediated deployment. First, contemporary smartphone form factors are awkward to maneuver close to the mouth of an older adult with limited neck mobility. Second, many low-income older adults use government-issued flip phones rather than smartphones, eliminating the patient-facing pathway for that subset. She further noted that smartphone ownership turns over every one to two years, and data migration between devices remains imperfect even on modern platforms.

On AI-mediated diagnosis, the consultant recommended that screening results be communicated to patients through a healthcare professional rather than directly from the application, consistent with the trust-mediation finding in §3.3. She indicated, separately, an independently held skepticism of AI applications in healthcare based on direct experience with AI-mediated customer service and medical-record summarization. Her recommendation that results be routed through a healthcare professional was offered against this background of skepticism, not despite it.

On deployment context, the consultant identified skilled nursing facilities and incarcerated populations as additional contexts in which the operator-trained-staff model would be applicable, alongside community-dwelling older adults with family caregivers.

The consultant had not been briefed on the CE Studio findings prior to the consultation. Her recommendations therefore offer a corroborating expert view from a different professional vantage rather than independent confirmation. The summary is released as a supplementary material.

\section{Discussion}
\subsection{Principal Finding}
The physical incapacity observed in §3.1 is not closed by improving the model. It is not closed by improving the hardware. It is closed by changing who holds the phone.

AI-powered geriatric health screening tools should be designed primarily as caregiver instruments. The caregiver---a family member, a community health worker, a nursing-home staff member, a clinical care worker---has the dexterity to perform the capture, the cognitive flexibility to interpret the result in conversation with the provider, and operational familiarity with the patient's body that the patient may not have for parts of her own mouth. The appropriate deployment unit is the caregiver--patient dyad, not the patient alone.

The asymmetry between expressed interest and embodied capacity reported in §3.4, and the corroborating expert recommendations in §3.5, point in the same direction (Table~\ref{tab:pivot-logic}).
