\subsection{The Finding in Context}
The pivot is not isolated to one cohort in Western New York. Three adjacent literatures, taken together, indicate that the cohort discovered something the field has been demonstrating piecemeal without naming it.

\textit{The operator population exists at scale.} The number of U.S. family caregivers helping older adults grew from approximately 18.2 million in 2011 to 24.1 million in 2022~\parencite{Wolff2025The}. Roughly three-quarters of disabled older adults receive informal home care, which remains the most common source of home care despite growth in formal services~\parencite{VanHoutven2020Informal}. The opportunity cost of informal elder care in the United States has been estimated at approximately \$522 billion annually~\parencite{Chari2015The}. The caregiver workforce is not a hypothetical population to be created; it exists at scale and performs analogous logistical and physical labor for the same patients.

\textit{Caregivers already perform analogous capture tasks.} A national survey of in-home video telehealth visits conducted by occupational therapy practitioners in the Veterans Health Administration found that caregivers frequently perform camera-related operations---holding, angling, repositioning the device, operating audio controls---when older adults' technical skills or capabilities are insufficient for the visit~\parencite{Gately2024Caregivers}. Qualitative work on telehomecare for homebound and bedridden older adults documents that caregivers learn to manage device issues and resolve technology challenges with experience, even when initial difficulties are substantial~\parencite{Onseng2024Expectation}. That caregivers can execute capture-related operations, has documented precedent in adjacent clinical workflows.
\textit{Institutional dental screening has already made this design move.} A U.S. survey of dental screening practice in nursing facilities found that approximately 90\% of completed dental assessments were performed not by dental staff, but rather by nurses and others~\parencite{Schroeder2018DENTAL}. Validated oral health screening instruments such as the interRAI Oral Health Screener are explicitly designed for non-dental caregivers to administer as part of routine resident assessment, with algorithmic flags that trigger care plans and dental referral~\parencite{Schoebrechts2024Comparison, Vandenbulcke2026Screening}. The institutional model is itself imperfect---the quality and downstream clinical impact of nurse-administered screening varies and remains under active investigation---but its operator paradigm is established. The community-dwelling design vocabulary has not caught up with the paradigm institutional dental care has already adopted.

The alignment of these three literatures with what emerged in the CE Studio gives the finding reach. The pivot is not a radical proposal; it is the alignment of community-dwelling AI mHealth design with an operator paradigm already present, at scale, in adjacent care contexts. The cited literatures describe analogous workflows rather than direct evidence of the proposed deployment, and whether the paradigm transfers cleanly to AI-mediated community-dwelling oral screening is itself the testable hypothesis the next stage of this work must address.
\subsection{Implications for Evaluation Pipelines}
The evaluation infrastructure for geriatric mHealth measures interest at the moment of demonstration; the variable that determines deployment success is embodied task completion under home conditions. The two are not the same, and the pipeline that conflates them produces favorable adoption forecasts the embodied user does not meet. In the present study, the half of the cohort who did not find the task easy to execute surfaced through observation of attempted use, not through stated preference. Given a survey instrument alone, the same half might have produced high adoption forecasts the embodied attempt did not meet.

Evaluation pipelines for geriatric AI mHealth should report instrumented capture-success rates under home conditions, caregiver-mediated task completion rates, and trust calibration against transparently disclosed model limitations. The Visit-Associated Logistics framework recently developed for older adults' medical visits names the multi-domain caregiver burden that current evaluation collapses into a single accessibility variable~\parencite{Ngo2025A}; the same multi-domain treatment is appropriate for evaluation of caregiver-mediated mHealth deployment. These measure deployment. Current questionnaires measure interest in deployment.
\subsection{Implications for Design}
Patient-first geriatric mHealth design treats capture aids as accessibility accommodations layered onto a smartphone-and-app substrate. The findings here recommend the inverse: the capture instrument designed for the embodied geriatric task is primary, and the smartphone-and-app substrate is one configuration among several.
The design floor for AI-powered geriatric screening tools is the harder case---the participant who cannot open her mouth wide enough, whose hands are not steady, whose phone makes no capture sound she can hear. The patient-facing interface is not this floor; it is the ceiling, available to the subset of older adults who can use it and prefer to.

Capture aids---retractors, voice-guided positioning, on-device quality feedback~\parencite{zhang2021wound}, audible capture confirmation at adjustable volume---become primary design considerations rather than just accessibility add-ons. The expert consultation proposed a concrete instantiation: an endoscope camera with integrated light, estimated at \$30--\$40 and distributable through public health campaigns, addressing both the mouth-exposure and hand-stability limitations in one instrument. Screen-equipped variants extend the design direction further: they eliminate the smartphone dependency entirely, allowing the trained operator to capture, view, and store screening images on a dedicated device.

Provider integration is load-bearing, not optional. A screening result that no provider receives is a recommendation with no destination. The older adults the tool is meant to serve will not generate the necessary follow-through unsupported; the result must enter a workflow that already includes them.

\subsection{Implications for Deployment}
Current geriatric mHealth deployment assumes the device will reach the patient and the patient will operate it. The populations the present findings recommend designing for---community-dwelling older adults with mobility limitations, nursing-facility residents, the unsupported elderly in low-income settings---are not currently reached at scale by this configuration. Two operator populations have documented existing infrastructure to reach them.

Family caregivers are the immediate population: 24.1 million U.S. adults already managing medications, appointments, and household logistics for older relatives~\parencite{Wolff2025The}, performing camera operations in adjacent care workflows~\parencite{Gately2024Caregivers}. Institutional caregivers---nursing-facility nurses and aides, assisted-living staff---are a second population already serving as the operators of oral health screening in their settings under validated instruments~\parencite{Schroeder2018DENTAL, Schoebrechts2024Comparison}. Both represent workforce reorganization rather than workforce creation. The visiting public health worker model proposed by the consultant offers a third configuration for older adults without family caregivers and not in institutional care; this is a workforce policy question outside the scope of the present design argument and warrants separate investigation.

Provider-initiated rollout addresses two problems at once. It establishes credibility against the scam vigilance participants and the facilitator returned to repeatedly. It also routes deployment through the trust relationship older adults already maintain---the dental office, the primary care provider, the nurse practitioner---rather than asking the older adult to extend trust to an unfamiliar mobile application unsupported.
\subsection{Heterogeneity, the Residual Pathway, and the Autonomy Question}
The cohort is not uniform on the embodied capacity to execute the task. One participant described her 80-year-old mother as a habitual user of an iPad: \textit{``her access to the world.''} Another observed:
\begin{quoting}
The perception is that we as seniors are very low on technology. But that is not always true.
\end{quoting}
The facilitator added:
\begin{quoting}
I think we all vary from high tech to low tech. You can't make general statements. It keeps us in the game.
\end{quoting}
These observations belong to the same dataset as the participants who could not execute the capture. If even a single cohort of thirteen contains both the tech-fluent 80-year-old iPad user and the 76-year-old who cannot open her mouth wide enough, the population the field serves is heterogeneous in ways the patient-first default cannot accommodate; larger and more diverse cohorts will not be more uniform. The 80-year-old iPad user and the 76-year-old who cannot open her mouth wide enough are members of the same population, and a design assumption that worked for the first cannot be the design assumption applied to both. The patient-facing pathway is not abandoned by the pivot; it is the residual mode, available to those who can execute the task themselves and prefer to. A design that begins with the caregiver-mediated dyad and exposes a patient-facing pathway for those who can use it serves both populations. A design that begins with the patient-facing assumption and exposes accessibility features for those who cannot serves the first population and largely neglects the second.

The caregiver-mediated model raises a legitimate autonomy concern: that designing around a caregiver could substitute for, rather than support, the older adult's agency over her own care. Properly implemented, the model is support with accompaniment rather than substitution~\parencite{Sun2026Experiences}. The older adult retains agency over the decision to be scanned at all, the frequency of scanning, which results are shared with which providers, whether to invite a caregiver to view results, and whether to migrate to the patient-facing pathway when capacity permits. Caregiver participation in capture does not transfer decisional authority for any of these. The substitution concern is real where caregiver participation extends beyond the embodied task it is recruited to perform; the model proposed here is bounded to that task. The residual patient-facing pathway preserves choice for those who do not need or want caregiver support.
\subsection{Limitations}
The cohort is small ($N=13$), drawn from a single region in Western New York, and demographically narrow (92.3\% White). These constrain claims about how the patterns reported here distribute across populations; they do not constrain the existence of the patterns themselves. Capture incapacity is not a phenomenon that becomes a different phenomenon in a more diverse sample. If even a cohort of thirteen surfaces the pattern consistently in a single afternoon, larger cohorts are unlikely to be free of it; the more reasonable expectation is that the pattern's prevalence will be greater, not smaller, in cohorts that more accurately reflect the geriatric population's distribution of physical capacity. The supplementary consultation involved a single consultant offering a corroborating expert view; convergence with one expert is suggestive of where a broader expert panel might land but is not itself confirmation.

The CE Studio elicits responses to a demonstration plus brief attempted use; longer-horizon deployment behavior in the caregiver-mediated dyad is hypothesized here, not observed. The caregiver-capability claim has documented precedent in adjacent telehealth workflows~\parencite{Gately2024Caregivers} but has not been observed in deployment for intraoral capture specifically; this is the most direct future-work question the present paper raises. Future work should test the caregiver-primary claim in larger, more diverse cohorts and under deployment conditions---specifically, in instrumented studies that measure capture success, caregiver burden, trust calibration, and clinical follow-through across configured caregiver pathways: family, professional, community health worker, and provider-initiated.
\section{Conclusion}
Seventy-nine percent of older U.S. adults own a smartphone. The geriatric dental disease burden is projected to nearly double by 2050. Twenty-four million Americans are family caregivers of older adults, and that population is growing. Every participant in our cohort wanted an AI-powered oral screening tool. Just over half believed they could use one without assistance. Approximately half found it easy to use; approximately half did not. During attempted use, participants could not open their mouths wide enough for the capture, and their hands were not steady enough to frame it.

The cost of continuing to design and evaluate as the field has been is recoverable from those numbers. Half of every geriatric cohort served by patient-first design is functionally designed out of the tool. The caregivers who already absorb the appointment burden continue absorbing it. The unsupported older adult continues to operate in the same threat environment as the scam attempts she has been trained to refuse. The disease burden continues to accumulate in a population whose conventional access pathways are constrained by cost and mobility. The tools shipped under the current evaluation pipeline continue producing favorable adoption forecasts from cohorts that, when asked to execute the task, cannot.

The conversation about geriatric mHealth has progressed past the access problem. The design vocabulary has the opportunity to progress with it. The patient-as-operator default was a reasonable inheritance from the populations for which mobile health was first designed; the patient population has shifted faster than the design vocabulary that serves it. The institutional dental screening field has already made the pivot the present findings recommend---non-dental caregivers as the primary operators of resident oral health assessment. The community-dwelling design vocabulary has the opportunity to follow.

What the field should do now is concrete. Evaluation pipelines should report instrumented embodied task completion under home conditions rather than interest at the moment of demonstration. Designers should treat the caregiver--patient dyad as the design floor and the patient-facing pathway as the ceiling. Deployment should route through the providers older adults already trust. Funders and reviewers should ask, of any new geriatric AI mHealth tool, who the embodied operator is---and whether the answer is the patient by default or the dyad by design.

