\section{Introduction}

Seventy-nine percent of U.S. adults aged 65+ own a smartphone; among those 50+, smartphone ownership reached 91\% by early 2025. Oral diseases account for 284.6 disability-adjusted life-years per 100,000, with 66\% of older adults having periodontitis---linked bidirectionally to diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and elevated Alzheimer's (+69\%) and Parkinson's (+43\%) risk. Caries burden is projected to nearly double by 2050. Traditional Medicare covers almost no dental care; roughly one in five older adults forgo dental visits due to cost.

The case for scalable, home-based AI-assisted screening is strong. Prevailing mHealth design for older adults assumes patient-as-operator: the patient holds the phone, captures data, receives results. This assumption inherited from younger, tech-literate populations does not align with the embodied constraints of geriatric users. Current mobile app UIs present significant barriers to older adults because they lack systematic tailoring to physical, sensory, and cognitive needs.

We report an iterative study: (1) formative Community Engagement Studio investigation of OralScan identifying the operator paradigm mismatch; (2) clinical consultation establishing design priorities; (3) system redesign focusing on cavity detection and caregiver-mediated capture; (4) preliminary validation of redesigned system performance. The work bridges two gaps: usability (who can operate the tool) and clinical utility (what clinical problem it actually solves).

\section{Materials and Methods}

\subsection{Original OralScan System}
OralScan captures intraoral images on a smartphone and returns segmentation overlays for six oral conditions: calculus/plaque, caries, oral lesions, gingivitis, hypodontia, and discoloration. On-device Laplacian-variance blur detection and quantized YOLOv11-Nano tooth-numbering screening provide real-time feedback. Accepted images (typically three per session) are submitted to cloud-based fine-tuned YOLOv11-XL detection integrated with Meta's Segment Anything Model 2.1. Bounding-box detections return as translucent overlays. Original model achieves mAP@0.50 of 0.748 averaged across six conditions. Full technical specifications appear in Appendix A.

\subsection{Community Engagement Studio Protocol}

\subsubsection{Participants and Design}
Session conducted in Western New York, 2025. University at Buffalo CTSI recruited via Buffalo Research Registry and community contacts. Eligibility: age 60+ or caregiver of older adult. N=13 attended (16 enrolled). Participants received \$50 compensation; all consented to audio recording.

Two-hour session structure: (1) 15-minute presentation, (2) 10-minute interactive demo, (3) 30-minute participant attempted use with staff available, (4) 70-minute facilitated discussion led by unaffiliated community facilitator (removes researcher-presence bias). Master transcript and summaries produced by CTSI staff per standard protocol. Two researchers independently performed inductive thematic analysis; disagreements resolved to consensus.

\subsubsection{Quantitative and Observational Metrics}
Observed during attempted use: mouth opening adequacy, hand stability, capture success. Post-session: 5-point Likert-scale responses on usability, willingness to pay, interest level.

