\subsubsection{Key Thematic Findings}

\paragraph{Capture Incapacity.} During attempted use, two physical limitations emerged consistently: (1) participants could not extend lips/cheeks sufficiently for intraoral exposure required by model, (2) hand tremor or dexterity loss prevented steady framing for on-device blur detector acceptance. These were observed directly, not inferred from post-hoc questionnaire. Contemporary smartphone cameras are sensor-adequate for caries imaging; barrier was embodied task execution, not optics.

\paragraph{Caregiver-as-Operator Framing.} A participant who had cared for an elderly mother reframed deployment: \textit{``I see this app more as a caregiver responsibility, not the elderly person. Caregivers would need the app on their phone.''} Facilitator, herself a former caregiver, endorsed immediately: \textit{``I wish I would have had that app''} when managing parent's appointments. Second caregiver participant confirmed. Framing emerged organically; research team role was limited to answering questions and demonstrating app.

\paragraph{Trust Mediation.} Participants expressed concerns distinct from usability: \textit{``AI is doing the diagnosis. That is scary.''} Another: \textit{``What if dentists don't know what I'm talking about?''} Model accuracy metrics (mAP@0.50 = 0.748) have no clinical referent; what participants measured was whether provider would honor result and whether workflow could act on it. Caregiver---typically younger, more app-fluent, familiar with patient's body---mediates this calibration.

\paragraph{Appointment Burden.} Caregivers described embodied cost of in-person appointments: wheelchair transport, exhaustion, mobility constraints. Screening tool reducing appointment frequency is principally a tool reducing caregiver burden, not patient burden.

