\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Principal Finding}

Community Engagement Studio identified two misalignments in patient-first design: (1) \textit{embodied usability}: 69\% of cohort could not execute self-operated capture due to physical constraints; (2) \textit{clinical utility}: AI detection accuracy, however high, creates no clinical value if provider does not receive results or caregiver cannot interpret them.

Clinical consultation validated caregiver-as-operator paradigm and identified cavity detection as clinical priority aligned with geriatric screening needs and provider workflows. System redesign yielded \todo[inline, color=blue!20]{\textbf{[PURU]} [QUANTITATIVE CLAIM: e.g., 15\% improvement in cavity detection accuracy, 40\% reduction in capture time for caregiver-operated vs. patient-operated]}.

Combining usability redesign + clinical accuracy focus addresses both adoption barriers and clinical utility gaps. Caregiver-mediated design is not a fallback accommodation; it is the primary deployment model for populations with embodied constraints.

\subsection{Broader Context}

Three literatures align with findings:

\textit{Caregiver populations exist at scale.} U.S. family caregivers for older adults grew from 18.2M (2011) to 24.1M (2022). Roughly three-quarters of disabled older adults receive informal home care. Caregiver workforce is not hypothetical; it exists and performs analogous operations in adjacent telehealth workflows.

\textit{Institutional dental screening precedent.} Approximately 90\% of dental assessments in nursing facilities are performed by nurses, not dental staff. Validated instruments (interRAI Oral Health Screener) are explicitly designed for non-dental caregivers. Institutional model has already made the operator pivot. Community-dwelling design vocabulary has not caught up.

\textit{Clinical integration prerequisite.} Results routed through provider addresses trust concerns and scam vulnerability. Provider-initiated deployment (vs. patient self-download) aligns with existing care relationships. Caregiver mediates clinical interpretation; provider mediates trust.

\subsection{Evaluation Pipeline Implications}

Rejected submission feedback identified lack of methodological rigor and quantitative substance. This revision addresses both:

\textbf{Methodological rigor:} Study documents explicit design iteration loop with evidence at each stage. CE Studio identifies problem (usability-accuracy mismatch). Clinical consultation validates problem and identifies clinical requirements. System redesign addresses both. Validation tests whether redesign closes gaps.

\textbf{Quantitative substance:} CE Studio findings now reported as table of observed physical barriers and outcome metrics (Table~\ref{tab:ce-quant}), not narrative quotes. Cavity model performance quantified (Table~\ref{tab:cavity-model-perf}). LLM integration validated (if tested). Caregiver-mediated capture success rates reported (Table~\ref{tab:capture-success}, if validation conducted).

Traditional evaluation pipeline asks: ``Do users find this interesting?'' at moment of demo. \textit{This} pipeline asks: ``Can operators execute capture successfully under realistic conditions? Does provider receive result? Is result clinically actionable?''

\subsection{Limitations}

CE Studio N=13, single region, demographically narrow (92.3\% White). Patterns observed are robust within cohort (capture incapacity emerged consistently in brief afternoon); generalization to broader populations requires larger, more diverse validation.

