  \item LLM tested on what range of cavity presentations?
  \item Caregiver-operated testing: only family caregivers, or also professional? Only specific conditions?
  \item Any known failure modes or edge cases?
\end{itemize}}

CE Studio elicits responses to brief attempted use; longer-horizon caregiver-mediated deployment behavior remains hypothesized. Validation study will test whether improved capture success rates in lab translate to sustained engagement in home use.

\subsection{Future Work}

Immediate next steps:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \todo[inline, color=blue!20]{\textbf{[PURU]} Report timeline and setting for validation deployment}
  \item Expand validation to larger, more diverse caregiver cohorts (family + professional + community health worker models)
  \item Test across patient populations (mobility-limited, institutionalized, low-income) to measure generalization
  \item Measure clinical downstream outcomes: Does provider act on results? Does patient receive appropriate follow-up care?
  \item Clinician-in-the-loop study: How do providers interpret LLM-summarized cavity findings? Any trust gaps?
  \item Multi-modal capture: Compare smartphone + endoscope camera variants in caregiver-operated workflow
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}

This work reframes geriatric oral screening design around the embodied constraint revealed by formative study: half the target population cannot execute self-operated capture. Clinical consultation validates caregiver-as-operator and identifies concrete clinical requirements (cavity detection priority). Redesigned system addresses both usability and clinical utility gaps through quantified model improvements and caregiver-mediated pipeline optimization.

Evaluation infrastructure that produced patient-first tools measures interest at demo, not embodied execution under home conditions. Tools shipped under this infrastructure reach populations through interfaces many cannot operate. Caregiver-mediated design is not an accessibility add-on; it is the primary deployment unit. This work demonstrates the design and validation approach required.

