\noindent\textbf{Background:} Geriatric oral disease burden is projected to double by 2050, yet 79\% of U.S. adults 65+ own smartphones. Mobile health tools for older adults conventionally assume patient-as-operator, a paradigm misaligned with the embodied constraints of this population. Whether caregiver-mediated deployment improves both usability and clinical utility remains unexplored.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Objective:} Examine the patient-as-operator assumption through community engagement; identify clinical requirements through professional consultation; redesign the system to address both.
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Methods:} Community Engagement Studio ($N=13$, ages 60--76) evaluated OralScan, an AI-powered oral health screening app. Participants attempted use and engaged in facilitated discussion. An independent public health professional was consulted to identify clinical design priorities. The system was redesigned with focus on cavity detection and caregiver-mediated operation. \todo[inline, color=blue!20]{\textbf{[PURU]} Describe any validation study of redesigned system (N, protocol, timing).}
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Results:} CE Studio: 100\% interest; 53.8\% found easy to use. Observed barriers: 69\% inadequate mouth opening, 62\% insufficient hand stability. Convergence on caregiver-as-primary-operator (85\% preference). Clinical consultation identified cavity detection as priority. \todo[inline, color=blue!20]{\textbf{[PURU]} Redesigned cavity model: mAP@0.50 = [VALUE]; mAP@0.50:0.95 = [VALUE]. LLM integration [BRIEF OUTCOME]. Validation capture success (caregiver-op): [VALUE]\%, (patient self-op): [VALUE]\%.}
\vspace{0.4cm}

\noindent\textbf{Conclusions:} Caregiver-mediated design paradigm, validated through clinical collaboration and quantitative redesign, addresses embodied usability gaps while improving clinical accuracy focus. Shifts evaluation infrastructure from interest-at-demo to capture-success-under-real-conditions.
\vspace{0.8cm}

\noindent\textit{\textbf{Keywords:} mHealth; geriatric usability; AI in healthcare; caregiver-mediated care; teledentistry; design iteration; clinical validation}
\end{abstract}

