\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Principal Finding}

Community Engagement Studio identified two misalignments in patient-first design: (1) \textit{embodied usability}: 69\% of cohort could not execute self-operated capture due to physical constraints; (2) \textit{clinical utility}: AI detection accuracy, however high, creates no clinical value if provider does not receive results or caregiver cannot interpret them.

Clinical consultation validated caregiver-as-operator paradigm and identified cavity detection as clinical priority aligned with geriatric screening needs and provider workflows. System redesign yielded \todo[inline, color=blue!20]{\textbf{[PURU]} [QUANTITATIVE CLAIM: e.g., 15\% improvement in cavity detection accuracy, 40\% reduction in capture time for caregiver-operated vs. patient-operated]}.

Combining usability redesign + clinical accuracy focus addresses both adoption barriers and clinical utility gaps. Caregiver-mediated design is not a fallback accommodation; it is the primary deployment model for populations with embodied constraints.

\subsection{Broader Context}

